There are several limitations of current GPU hardware in scaling large language models to enormous size. First, the large number of parameters to be processed by the GPU can lead to memory bandwidth bottlenecks, making it difficult to train models with more than a few billion parameters. This is because the GPU needs to pull in data from main memory and send it back to the main memory to compute the data, which can slow down the overall process. Second, the large amount of data required to train such large models can only be stored on slower, higher-capacity storage devices such as NVMe drives, which may not provide enough bandwidth to keep up with the demand of the GPU. Third, the energy requirements for running such large models can be significant, putting a strain on the power supply and potentially leading to higher energy costs. Finally, the physical space required to house the hardware for such large models can be prohibitive, especially considering that it may be necessary to upgrade existing hardware to accommodate larger models. As a result, the current state of GPU hardware has limitations when it comes to scaling large language models to enormous sizes, and improved hardware will be necessary to achieve this goal.

Wireguard does not support multiple tunneling unlike IKE, which can only allow one VPN tunnel to be established at a given time, further strengthening its security.
